To resolve the "serious lag" when switching screens, I will implement a **"Keep Alive" (Persistent View)** architecture for the main screens.

**The Problem:**
Currently, every time you navigate between "Sales" and "Items", React destroys the old screen (and all its heavy DOM nodes for images/grids) and builds the new one from scratch. With 200+ items and images, this destruction/creation cycle is CPU-intensive, causing the lag.

**The Solution:**
I will modify the layout so that the main screens (`Sales`, `Receipts`, `Items`, `Settings`) remain mounted in the DOM once they are loaded. When you navigate, we simply toggle their visibility (`display: none` vs `display: flex`). This makes switching screens **instantaneous** because the browser doesn't have to repaint or recalculate the heavy lists.

**Changes:**
1.  **`components/Layout.tsx`**: Replace the standard `Routes` with a manual visibility manager. It will lazy-load screens (only render them once you visit them) and then keep them alive.
2.  **`screens/SalesScreen.tsx`**: Update the header title logic to ensure it only updates the global header when the Sales screen is actually visible.

